Case Study Unit #8: Classification Using XGBoost, Random Forest & SVM¶

By: Armando Vela & Jeff Washburn

Date: 10/20/2020

Abstract¶

A classification model was used to predict a binary target variable of an anonymized dataset provided by the case study. The three methods used were eXtreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost), Random Forest, & Support Vector Machine (SVM). After running each model and comparing the accuracy for each, the XGBoost model was considered the best fitting model with an accuracy score of about 0.78. For future research, we may be able to increase our scores by looking into using Principal Component Analysis on the data as well as hyperparameter tuning.

Introduction¶

For this case study, we were given an anonymized dataset that contained no metadata or data dictionary, with the only labeled column being our "target" variable. The dataset consisted of 114,321 rows and 133 columns (114 numeric vs 19 categorical). See figure 1 for a breakdown of the dataset.

With that said, the requirements for a successful study were as follows:

  • Build 3 tuned models: XGBoost, Random Forest, SVM
  • Show log loss and accuracy for XGBoost & Random Forest on out of fold predictions.
  • Show accuracy for SVM on a validation set.
  • Time how long it takes to do a sample of 1000, 2000, 5000, 10,000 rows in the SVM. What is the rough scaling of SVM with sample size?

Within the Methods section we will go over the basics of each model, the associated metrics to score the model fit, and how we prepared & modeled the data.

Methods¶

Model Review¶

XGBoost:
XGBoost is an optimized distributed gradient boosting library designed to be highly efficient, flexible and portable. It implements machine learning algorithms under the Gradient Boosting framework. XGBoost provides a parallel tree boosting (also known as GBDT, GBM) that solve many data science problems in a fast and accurate way

Reference: XGBoost website

Random Forest:
Random forest consists of a large number of individual decision trees that operate as an ensemble. Each individual tree in the random forest spits out a class prediction and the class with the most votes becomes our models prediction

Reference: Tony Yiu - Understanding Random Forest

SVM:
The objective of the support vector machine algorithm is to find a hyperplane in an N-dimensional space(N the number of features) that distinctly classifies the data points.

Refernce: Rohith Gandhi - Support Vector Machine - Introduction to Machine Learning Algorithms

Scoring Metrics¶

LogLoss:
A measure of the difference between two probability distributions for a given random variable or set of events. Reference: TowardsDataScience

Accuracy:
Accuracy is closeness of the measurements to a specific value. Reference: Accuracy Definition

Preparing & Modeling the Data¶

Initial Split:
The data was split into a training and test set using a stratified shuffle split before further analysis was done. A stratified shuffle split was used since the ratio of target = 1 vs target = 0 is skewed 76% to 24% respectively. See figure 2 below.

Reasoning for initial split: In the event that we are going to be sending out this model to production, by splitting out an initial test set we can train and cross validate our model with the training set and if we recieved acceptable scoring metrics then we can further test against the test set before sending out to production.

PreProcessing Training Data:
In order to be able to run our models correctly, we needed to perform some data transformation methods prior to any models being created. With that said, we elected to use the StandardScaler method for our numerical values and OneHotEncoding for our categorical values.

Figure 3: PreProcessor

  • StandardScaler: This method normalizes (ie. standardizes) the amounts in each column to a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. For example, lets say one column had a scale of 1-10 but a second column had a scale of 100,000 - 1,000,000; since these two columns are very different in scales the StandardScaler will look to standardized and create a common scale. This is essential when creating a machine learning model since without scaling you would be overweighting larger scaled columns.
  • OneHotEncoding: This method is a way of turning categorical features into a numerical value that can be used within a machine learning model. For example, lets say you had one column with 3 categories (red, white, or blue). Since the machine learning models used cannot read this type of data, OneHotEncoding creates 3 new columns and places a 1 value if it is the correct color for the row or a 0 value for all other colors. See figure below.

Figure 4: OneHotEncoding Example

Using Training Data for Modeling:
After processing the data for our machine learning models, we then fit three different types of models (Random Forest, XGBoost, and Linear SVM). To help validate, we performed a stratified 5 fold cross validation and compared the mean accuracy scores for each and the mean logloss scores for XGBoost and Random Forest.

Finally, we selected our best model, which was a XGBoost model, and tested against the initial training set to determine overall fit.

Prepare Data¶

Split the data into train and test set¶

The data will be split into a training and test set before further analysis will be done. With that said, since the ratio of target = 1 vs target = 0 is skewed 76% to 24% respectively, we will be performing a stratified shuffle spit on the data.

Note: this test set is not to be touched until we are close to final production. In other words, we will be using the training set to train and cross validate our model. Once we have recieved a good enough accuracy, then we can try on the test set before sending out to production.

In [9]:
split = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=1, test_size=0.2, random_state=50)

for train_index, test_index in split.split(df, df['target']):
    strat_train_set = df.loc[train_index]
    strat_test_set = df.loc[test_index]

SVM on subset of data (500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000)¶

In [38]:
from sklearn.svm import SVC
In [39]:
def doSVM(subsets, logProgress=True):
    retDf = pd.DataFrame(columns=['ClassificationMethod', 'Accuracy', 'LogLoss', 'TrainingSize', 'TrainingDurationInSecs'])
    for idx, subsetSize in enumerate(subsets):
        # time it
        start = time.perf_counter()
        
        # Create SVC model
        #model = LinearSVC(tol=1, max_iter = 5000)
        model = SVC(verbose=True)
        kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
        
        # subset the data training data into specified size
        X_train_subset = X_train[:subsetSize]
        y_train_subset = y_train[:subsetSize]
        
        # Cross validation on dataset
        #results = cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring = 'accuracy')
        results = cross_validate(model, X_train_subset, y_train_subset, cv=kfold, scoring = 'accuracy')
        
        # Stop the timing
        duration = time.perf_counter() - start
        if (logProgress):
            txt = "Subset size: {0}: Accuracy: {1:0.4f}: Duration: {2:0.4f}"
            print(txt.format(subsetSize, results['test_score'].mean(), duration))
        
        # update the dataframe w/ results
        name='SVM-' + str(subsetSize)
        retDf.loc[idx] = [name, results['test_score'].mean(), np.nan, subsetSize, duration]
    return(retDf)
